{"id":"2010.02722","submitter":"Felix Gotti","authors":"David F. Anderson and Felix Gotti","title":"Bounded and finite factorization domains","comments":"40 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An integral domain is atomic if every nonzero nonunit factors into\nirreducibles. Let $R$ be an integral domain. We say that $R$ is a bounded\nfactorization domain if it is atomic and for every nonzero nonunit $x \\in R$,\nthere is a positive integer $N$ such that for any factorization $x = a_1 \\cdots\na_n$ of $x$ into irreducibles $a_1, \\dots, a_n$ in $R$, the inequality $n \\le\nN$ holds. In addition, we say that $R$ is a finite factorization domain if it\nis atomic and every nonzero nonunit in $R$ factors into irreducibles in only\nfinitely many ways (up to order and associates). The notions of bounded and\nfinite factorization domains were introduced by D. D. Anderson, D. F. Anderson,\nand M. Zafrullah in their systematic study of factorization in atomic integral\ndomains. Here we provide a survey of some of the most relevant results on\nbounded and finite factorization domains.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Oct 2020 13:47:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-07"}
